  "The rate constant of a reaction from its temperature and concentration": "",
  "The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation (pH = pKa + log[A-]/[HA]) calculates the pH of a buffer using the pKa of the weak acid and the ratio of conjugate base to weak acid concentrations.": "",
  "What does pKa represent?": "",
  "The negative logarithm of the acid dissociation constant": "",
  "The total concentration of acid in a given solution volume": "",
  "The pressure at which an acid begins to decompose": "",
  "The temperature at which an acid reaches its boiling point": "",
  "pKa = -log(Ka), where Ka is the acid dissociation constant. A lower pKa means a stronger acid. The pKa is important in buffer calculations.": "",
  "What is meant by 'dynamic equilibrium' in a buffer system?": "",
  "The forward and reverse reactions occur at equal rates simultaneously": "",
  "The reaction has completely stopped and no changes are occurring": "",
  "Only the forward reaction is occurring while the reverse has stopped": "",
  "The buffer components are continuously being added from outside": "",
  "In a buffer at dynamic equilibrium, the weak acid and its conjugate base are constantly interconverting at equal rates. This allows the buffer to respond to added acid or base.": "",
  "What is the 'buffering range' of a buffer?": "",
  "The pH range (typically pKa plus or minus 1) where the buffer works effectively": "",
  "The temperature range over which the buffer solution remains in liquid form": "",
  "The volume range of solution that can fit inside a standard laboratory flask": "",
  "The concentration range at which the buffer components begin to precipitate": "",
  "The buffering range is typically pKa +/- 1 pH unit. Within this range, the buffer effectively resists pH changes. Outside this range, the buffer becomes ineffective.": "",
  "What is the difference between a weak acid and a strong acid in buffer context?": "",
  "A weak acid partially dissociates while a strong acid fully dissociates in water": "",
  "A weak acid has a higher concentration than a strong acid in any solution": "",
  "A weak acid is always safer to handle while a strong acid is always dangerous": "",
  "A weak acid cannot form salts while a strong acid always forms salts quickly": "",
  "A weak acid only partially dissociates in water, establishing equilibrium. A strong acid fully dissociates. Buffers require weak acids because the undissociated form is needed to neutralize added base.": "",
  "Define the term 'conjugate acid-base pair.'": "",
  "Two species that differ by exactly one proton and work together in a buffer": "",
  "Two strong acids that react together to produce a neutral salt and water": "",
  "Two solutions with the same pH that are mixed together in a laboratory": "",
  "Two bases that have the same concentration but different chemical formulas": "",
  "A conjugate acid-base pair consists of two species that differ by one proton (H+). For example, CH3COOH and CH3COO- are a conjugate pair. This pairing is what makes buffers work.": "",
